"Unger N., Shindell D.T., Wang J.S.","Climate forcing by the on-road transportation and power generation sectors",2009,"Atmospheric Environment","43","19",,"3077","3085",,,10.1016/j.atmosenv.2009.03.021,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-65649133661&partnerID=40&md5=1a3ca35a0cbaeb4320a8e7ba44fc51ef","NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY 10025, United States; Center for Climate Systems Research, Columbia University, New York, NY 10025, United States; Environmental Defense Fund, New York, NY 10010, United States","Unger, N., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY 10025, United States, Center for Climate Systems Research, Columbia University, New York, NY 10025, United States; Shindell, D.T., NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies, New York, NY 10025, United States; Wang, J.S., Environmental Defense Fund, New York, NY 10010, United States","The on-road transportation (ORT) and power generation (PG) sectors are major contributors to carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions and a host of short-lived radiatively-active air pollutants, including tropospheric ozone and fine aerosol particles, that exert complex influences on global climate. Effective mitigation of global climate change necessitates action in these sectors for which technology change options exist or are being developed. Most assessments of possible energy change options to date have neglected non-CO2 air pollutant impacts on radiative forcing (RF). In a multi-pollutant approach, we apply a global atmospheric composition-climate model to quantify the total RF from the global and United States (U.S.) ORT and PG sectors. We assess the RF for 2 time horizons: 20- and 100-year that are relevant for understanding near-term and longer-term impacts of climate change, respectively. ORT is a key target sector to mitigate global climate change because the net non-CO2 RF is positive and acts to enhance considerably the CO2 warming impacts. We perform further sensitivity studies to assess the RF impacts of a potential major technology shift that would reduce ORT emissions by 50% with the replacement energy supplied either by a clean zero-emissions source (S1) or by the PG sector, which results in an estimated 20% penalty increase in emissions from this sector (S2). We examine cases where the technology shift is applied globally and in the U.S. only. The resultant RF relative to the present day control is negative (cooling) in all cases for both S1 and S2 scenarios, global and U.S. emissions, and 20- and 100-year time horizons. The net non-CO2 RF is always important relative to the CO2 RF and outweighs the CO2 RF response in the S2 scenario for both time horizons. Assessment of the full impacts of technology and policy strategies designed to mitigate global climate change must consider the climate effects of ozone and fine aerosol particles. © 2009 Elsevier Ltd.","Aerosols; Electric power; Ozone; PHEV; Radiative forcing; Transportation","Air pollutants; Climate effects; Climate forcing; Climate models; Electric power; Energy changes; Fine aerosols; Global climate changes; Global climates; PHEV; Policy strategies; Radiative forcing; Road transportations; Sensitivity studies; Technology changes; Technology shifts; Time horizons; Tropospheric ozones; Zero-emissions; Air pollution; Atmospheric aerosols; Atmospheric composition; Carbon dioxide; Electric power measurement; Motor transportation; Ozone; Roads and streets; Sodium compounds; Technology; Climate change; carbon dioxide; carbon monoxide; methane; nitrogen oxide; sulfur dioxide; volatile organic compound; aerosol; atmospheric pollution; carbon dioxide; chemical composition; climate effect; climate forcing; climate modeling; emission; global climate; ozone; power generation; radiative forcing; road transport; aerosol; air pollutant; article; atmosphere; electric power plant; environmental impact; geographic distribution; global climate; model; priority journal; radiative forcing; traffic; United States; North America; United States",,"carbon dioxide, 124-38-9, 58561-67-4; carbon monoxide, 630-08-0; methane, 74-82-8; nitrogen oxide, 11104-93-1; sulfur dioxide, 7446-09-5",,,,"Bell, M.L., McDermott, A., Zeger, S.L., Samet, J.M., Dominici, F., Ozone and short-term mortality in 95 U.S. urban communities 1987-2000 (2004) J. Am. Med. Assoc., 292, pp. 2372-2378; Berntsen, T., Fuglestvedt, J.S., Joshi, M., Shine, K.P., Stuber, N., Sausen, R., Li, L., Ponater, M., Climate response to regional emissions of ozone precursors: sensitivities and warming potentials (2005) Tellus Ser. B, 57, pp. 283-304; Bond, T.C., Streets, D.G., Yarber, K.F., Nelson, S.M., Woo, J.-H., Klimont, Z., A technology-based global inventory of black and organic carbon emissions from combustion (2004) J. Geophys. Res., 109, pp. D14203. , 10.1029/2003JD003697; Chiu, K., Lei, Y., Zhang, Y., Chen, D., Breathing better: linking energy and GHG reduction to health benefits in China (2007) China Environ. Ser., 9, pp. 117-126; Daniel, J.S., Solomon, S., On the climate forcing of carbon monoxide (1998) J. Geophys. Res., 103, pp. 13249-13260; Dockery, D.W., An association between air pollution and mortality in six U.S. cities (1993) The New England J. Med., 329, pp. 1753-1759; Electric Power Research Institute (EPRI), (2007) Environmental Assessment of Plug-in Hybrid Electric Vehicles, 1. , http://www.epri-reports.org, Nationwide Greenhouse Gas Emissions Report 1015325; (2006), http://www.eei.org/industry_issues/energy_infrastructure/generation/index.htm(2006), http://www.eia.doe.gov/fuelelectric.htmlForster, P., Changes in atmospheric constituents and in radiative forcing (2007) Climate Change 2007: the Physical Science Basis, pp. 131-215. , Cambridge University Press, New York; Fuglestvedt, J.S., Berntsen, T., Myhre, G., Rypdal, K., Skeie, R.B., Climate forcing from the transport sectors (2008) Proc. Nat. Acad. Sci., 105, pp. 454-458; Hadley, S.W., Tsvetkova, A., (2008) Potential Impacts of Plug-